{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 11:24:37.445815", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\\nTarget network: scalable SDN spine–leaf (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1), hosts host_1_1..host_2_2 (10.0.0.0/24). Management network 20.0.0.0/24 (spine_1=20.0.0.1, leaf_1=20.0.0.2, leaf_2=20.0.0.3). Controller at 20.0.0.100.\\n\\n1) Executive summary\\n- The network exhibits partial, inconsistent L2/L3 connectivity among the 10.0.0.0/24 hosts. Two hosts (10.0.0.2 and 10.0.0.3) can ping each other reliably; the other hosts show ARP failures and are largely unreachable from peers.\\n- OVS bridge objects on the switches (ovs-system / per-switch bridge) are in a DOWN state while their physical interfaces remain UP and enslaved to the (down) bridge. Many host ARP entries are in FAILED state.\\n- Likely root cause: OVS dataplane/bridge layer is non-functional (bridges down / OVS not operating correctly) causing L2 forwarding/ARP resolution to fail; this produces the observed asymmetric/partial reachability.\\n\\n2) Observed symptoms (high level)\\n- Mixed reachability:\\n  - host_1_2 (10.0.0.2) <-> host_2_1 (10.0.0.3): successful pings (0% loss, low RTT).\\n  - Many other host-to-host ping attempts show \"Destination Host Unreachable\" or 100% packet loss / timeouts.\\n- Host ARP/neighbour state:\\n  - Several hosts show FAILED neighbour entries for peers (ARP resolution failures).\\n- Switch bridge state:\\n  - The OVS bridge device(s) (ovs-system and the named per-switch bridge) are reported as DOWN on leaf and spine devices while their physical ports are UP and marked as master of the (down) bridge.\\n\\n3) Tests performed and concrete results (evidence)\\n- Reachability summary (tool-collected): many host pair reachability results were unknown/timeouts; notable concrete results:\\n  - host_1_2 -> host_2_1: 4 packets transmitted, 4 received, 0% loss; rtt ~1.6–3 ms.\\n  - host_2_1 -> host_1_2: 4/4, 0% loss; rtt ~2.47–3.42 ms.\\n  - host_1_2 -> host_1_1: 4 transmitted, 0 received, plus errors; \"From 10.0.0.2 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\" returned.\\n  - Other pairs (e.g., to/from host_2_2 and host_1_1) showed 100% loss or timed out.\\n\\n- Host neighbour (ARP) outputs:\\n  - host_1_1: ip neigh shows\\n    - 10.0.0.3 dev eth0 FAILED\\n    - 10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\\n    - 10.0.0.4 dev eth0 FAILED\\n  - host_1_2: ip neigh shows\\n    - 10.0.0.1 dev eth0 FAILED\\n    - 10.0.0.4 dev eth0 FAILED\\n    - 10.0.0.3 dev eth0 lladdr 0a:e3:2f:bb:d9:19 STALE\\n  - host_2_1: ip neigh shows\\n    - 10.0.0.1 dev eth0 FAILED\\n    - 10.0.0.2 dev eth0 lladdr 16:71:be:2b:e2:1c STALE\\n    - 10.0.0.4 dev eth0 FAILED\\n  - host_2_2: (no neighbour output collected, but ping/timeouts show likely similar ARP problems)\\n\\n- Switch (OVS) network configs (examples):\\n  - leaf_1:\\n    - eth0..eth2 show \"master ovs-system state UP\" but ovs-system interface and bridge \"leaf_1\" are state DOWN:\\n      - ovs-system: state DOWN\\n      - leaf_1 (bridge): state DOWN\\n      - eth3 (management) has 20.0.0.2 and is UP.\\n  - leaf_2: same pattern — per-port eth0..eth2 \"master ovs-system state UP\" but ovs-system and bridge are DOWN; eth3 has 20.0.0.3 and is UP.\\n  - spine_1: ovs-system and bridge down, eth2 has 20.0.0.1 (management) and is UP.\\n\\n4) Analysis and localization\\n- Symptom localization:\\n  - The problem is at the L2/dataplane layer handled by OVS on the SDN switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1). Evidence: OVS bridge devices on all switches are DOWN while the underlying physical ports remain administratively UP (enslaved to the bridge). When the bridge is down, kernel bridging/datapath forwarding does not occur even though interfaces show link-up.\\n  - Host-layer symptoms (FAILED ARP entries, \"Destination Host Unreachable\") are consistent with inability to resolve ARP/forward L2 frames through the switches.\\n  - Partial connectivity (10.0.0.2 <-> 10.0.0.3) is likely due to cached ARP/neighbour entries or an ephemeral path that remained from before the datapath failure; these stale caches can allow a single pair to communicate until timeouts/refresh. The fact that only one host pair can reliably communicate suggests that most L2 forwarding is broken and only pre-existing/locally cached mappings remain usable.\\n\\n- Likely impacted components:\\n  - OVS bridge/daemon or per-switch bridge configuration on leaf_1, leaf_2 and spine_1.\\n  - L2 dataplane between leafs and spine for 10.0.0.0/24 hosts (data-plane).\\n  - Host ARP resolution and intra-subnet connectivity for the 10.0.0.0/24 hosts.\\n\\n5) Root-cause hypothesis\\n- The immediate root cause is failure of the OVS bridging layer on the switches: OVS bridge devices (ovs-system and named per-switch bridge instances) are DOWN. This prevents L2 bridging/datapath forwarding for host-facing ports even though the physical interfaces show link-up and the management interfaces (20.0.0.x) remain configured and active.\\n- Possible upstream reasons (not confirmed by current data): OVS user-space/service not running, misconfiguration of bridges, corrupted datapath, or controller operations that changed/deleted flows/bridges. (Note: these are hypotheses about why the bridge is down — the evidence at hand shows the bridge state but not the precise failure mechanism.)\\n\\n6) Impact assessment\\n- Hosts 10.0.0.1 and 10.0.0.4 are effectively isolated from most peers (ARP failures, unable to ping).\\n- Host pair 10.0.0.2 and 10.0.0.3 retain bidirectional connectivity (likely transient).\\n- Controller reachability over management network not investigated here; however management IPs on switches exist and show RX/TX counters — management plane may be intact while data plane (OVS bridging) is not.\\n\\n7) Key evidence snippets\\n- ip neigh on host_1_1: \"10.0.0.3 dev eth0 FAILED\", \"10.0.0.2 dev eth0 FAILED\", \"10.0.0.4 dev eth0 FAILED\"\\n- ping result (host_1_2 -> host_2_1): \"4 packets transmitted, 4 received, 0% packet loss, rtt min/avg/max ~1.6/2.16/2.98 ms\"\\n- ping result (host_1_2 -> host_1_1): \"4 packets transmitted, 0 received, +4 errors, 100% packet loss\" with \"From 10.0.0.2 icmp_seq=1 Destination Host Unreachable\"\\n- leaf_1 ip addr / ifconfig excerpt: ovs-system state DOWN; bridge leaf_1 state DOWN; eth0..eth2 show \"master ovs-system state UP\" but bridge still DOWN; eth3 inet 20.0.0.2/24 present.\\n\\n8) Conclusion (diagnostic)\\n- There is an anomaly: OVS bridge/datapath functionality on the SDN switches is non-operational (bridges DOWN). This has caused L2 forwarding failures resulting in ARP failures and largely broken host-to-host connectivity in the 10.0.0.0/24 data network. The failure is localized to the switch dataplane layer (OVS) on leaf_1, leaf_2 and spine_1; effects are observed as FAILED ARP entries and ICMP unreachable/timeouts on hosts. The management plane (20.0.0.0/24) appears present on switch interfaces, but the OVS datapath itself is down.\\n\\nIf you want, I can next (upon your instruction) gather additional focused evidence to verify the OVS/control-plane status (e.g., ovs-vsctl show, systemctl status for openvswitch, vtysh/frr checks, controller connection state) or run additional traces to confirm whether the controller is involved in the bridge state changes. (No remediation performed here per request.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='231736b8-7af3-4099-b67b-0906a8efa444'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
